===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|やなぎ|yomi=k|alt=楊,楊柳}}
{{swp|ja:ヤナギ}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}. Cognate with {{cog|xug|柳|tr=yanāji}}, {{cog|mvi|柳|tr=yanagzï}}, {{cog|ryu|柳|tr=yanaji}} (likely all early borrowings from Middle Japanese).

The ultimate derivation is {{unc|ja|nocap=1}}, with several theories presented in reference works.  Some of the main theories:

* Appears to be derived from a compound, possibly {{com|ja|矢|tr1=ya|t1=[[arrow]]|な|tr2=na|pos2=Old Japanese [[apophonic|apophonic]] form of possessive particle {{ja-r|の}}|木|tr3=ki|t3=[[tree]]}}.<ref name="NKD">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten Concise|柳}}</ref> {{rendaku2|ki|gi}}
* Alternatively, the ''ya'' might be from the {{m|ja|字音|tr=jion||[[character]] [[reading]]}} of {{der|ja|ltc|-}} {{ltc-l|楊|[[willow]]}} + {{cog|ja|木|tr=ki||tree}}.<ref name="NKD"/>

Considering the existence of synonymous form {{ja-r|やぎ}} that appears in certain compounds, the medial ''na'' element is likely the particle.

First cited to roughly 759 {{CE}}, in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' collection of poetry with the phonetic ''{{w| Man'yōgana}}'' spelling {{lang|ja|也奈宜}}.<ref name="NKD"/>

